<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title></title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Paul Bowen QC</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">, Doughty Street Chambers (LAI 009)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">QC </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">specialising in public law and human rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> at Doughty Street chambers in London, with a particular interest in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with mental and physical disabilities, children, immigration detainees, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the families of those who die in custody</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I wish to highlight </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the risks posed by the proposals contained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the Government’s Consultation Document – the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">euphemistically </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">named ‘Transforming Legal Aid’ document.  Over 16,000 individuals and organisations responded to the consultation, the overwhelming majority of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">whom expressed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> opposition and deep concern abou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">its proposals</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Despite well-publicised U-turns from </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Lord Chancellor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in relation, primarily, to criminal legal aid, the response of the Government to the proposals for civil legal aid has not addressed these concerns.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  The focus of my submissions wil</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l be on the effect these proposals will have on my particular area of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">expertise</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, public law.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I must declare my interest at the outset - much of my work is legally aided, so if these proposals are to be passed into law </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">my ability to continue representing my</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> vulnerable clients will be further compromised</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  But I hope </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Committee </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">will accept that my criticisms are not wholly from self-interest. </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">My </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">concerns </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">about the proposals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are, broadly, twofold.  First, the proposals undermine the rule of law and its ess</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ential corollary, the principle of equality before the law.  Second</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, the economic case for the proposals is deeply flawed, as the downstream costs of the changes are likely to far outweigh any savings that might be made.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I have read and agree with the submission of Dr. Nick Armstrong who has focussed on the costs argument.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I am going to focus on the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rule of law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, not only because that is my area of expertise but because </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I fear </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">these changes are symptomatic of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">profou</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nd and damaging</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> attack on the rule of law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, illustrated by this Government’s consistent criticism of the Human Rights Act 1998 and its threat to withdraw the United Kingdom from the European Convention on Human Rights</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">What is the rule of law, and why is it</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> important?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> “The maintenance of the rule of law is in every way as important in a free society as the democratic franchise.  In our society the rule of law rests upon twin foundations: the Sovereignty of the Queen in Parliament in making the law and the s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">overeignty of the Queen’s courts in interpreting and applying the law” (Lord Bridge of Harwich, X v Morgan-Grampian Ltd [1991] AC 1, 48).  </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The rule of law provides the underpinning to the successful operation of all of the institutions of a democratic soc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">iety, which are in turn a necessary precondition to its economic and social success, as the President of the Supreme Court, Lord Neuberger, explained in a recent talk</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  He cited a recent </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">book, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Why Nations Fail</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, in which two US </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">academics, Professors Daron </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Acemoglu and James A. Robinson, offer an explanation as to why some nations </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">succeed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">while others </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">do </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">not.  The key is whether they are ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nclusive’ or ‘extractive’ societies.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As they explain:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘Extractive political institutions concentrate power in the hands</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> of a narrow elite and place few constraints on the exercise of this power. Economic institutions are then often structured by this elite to extract resources from the rest of society (in other words, they exist in order to enrich the elite by ensuring the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> transfer of society’s wealth into their hands, or overseas bank accounts).</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Institutions in inclusive societies</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, on the other hand,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> encourage economic activity, productivity and innovation, thereby incentivising investment and economic growth</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and providing</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the right environment for the provision of essential infrastructure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> necessary to foster economic activity</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: roads, regulat</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ion, health care, and education</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  However, social and economic infrastructures are not sufficient.  Economic activity, productivity an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">d innovation will only thrive, as Adam Smith explained</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more than two centuries ago</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Wealth of Nations</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, in an environment which affords secure property rights and effective freedom of contract.  Accordingly,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> as Lord Neuberger went on:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“... the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> State has to provide fair and clear laws equally applicable to all, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">a legal system readily available to all, and an effective and efficient court structure readily accessible to all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. It must, in other words, secure the rule of law.  And here we see the li</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nk back to inclusive political institutions: only they can effectively guarantee the rule of law, which itself underpins the growth of inclusive economic institutions. As they have it, the institutions of inclusive states operate as a virtuous circle.”</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> (Em</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">phasis added)</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The rule of law is therefore an essential underpinning of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a State’s </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">economic success.  But it does not stop </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">with secure property rights and freedom of contract</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tates in which executive power is exercised arbitrarily are not only economical</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ly unsuccessful, but socially unsuccessful</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Other rights must therefore be protected.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unfair allocation of resources</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">discrimination against vulnerable and minority groups, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gross </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">invasions of privacy</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">de</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">privations of personal property,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> arbitrary det</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ntions,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">torture and ‘disappearances’</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> all staging-posts on the road to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a society</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> where the rule of law is undermined</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Judicial review is the mechanism by which executive government </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the UK </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is held to account by members of the public through the courts</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  It is the rule of law in action.  The willingness of an independent judiciary to hold the executive to account may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">occasionally anger</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> and discom</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">fit</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> Ministers and other elected officials</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (including a number of members of the Labour Government)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, but it is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> fundamental to the operation of a democracy: without it the executive is free to ignore the laws made by Parliament. As Sir Stephen Sedley puts it</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘... the governance of the state is a prime concern of the rule of law: government beyond law is tyranny.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  ... [I]f the judges are not prepared to speak for it, a constitution is nothing.  Stalin’s successive constitutions for the USSR set out rows of shining rights, but with courts that lacked the means or the will or both to make anything of them they prote</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cted nobody and left the political executive in undisputed command of society.’</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:7.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">There is nothing undemocratic about judicial review of executive action.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The Courts do not substitute their views for those of the democratic decision-maker.  Their role is on</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ly to ensure that the decision has been taken</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in accordance with the very laws that Parliament has itself passed</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">As Lord Bingham </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">said in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A v Home Secretary</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> [2005] 2 AC 68 (the Belmarsh detainees case), at para 42:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“It is of course true that the judges in</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> this country are not elected and are not answerable to Parliament.  It is also of course true ... that Parliament, the executive and the courts have different functions.  But the function of independent judges charged to interpret and apply the law is uni</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">versally recognised as a cardinal feature of the modern democratic state, a cornerstone of the rule of law itself.  The Attorney General is fully entitled to insist on the proper limits of judicial authority, but he is wrong to stigmatise judicial decision</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-making as in some way undemocratic.”</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Judicial review creates a culture of transparency and accountability of executive action that is necessary for the rule of law to have any meaning.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">An essential component of the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rule of law is the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">availability of leg</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">al aid.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Since its introduction in 1949, legal aid </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">has allowed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">poor and vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">people – </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">if no longer ordinary people, who have been gradually excluded as the means test has become increasingly draconian</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> – to have genuine access to justice on the same t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">erms as the rich.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the area I am particularly concerned with i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t has allowed disabled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">adults and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">children to challenge unlawful </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">community care decisions and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">policies of local authorities; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">local residents to challenge developments that put their homes, en</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">vironment and livelihoods at risk; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">mentally disordered individuals to challenge the conditions of their detention; </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">those who are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">unlawfully detained </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">by the police to obtain redress; the families of those that die in state custody to be represented at their</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> loved one’s inquest; victims of crime to challenge decisions of the CPS not to prosecute their attacker</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">; and the victims of torture and abuse by British troops abroad to secure independent investigations into those claims.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This process, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in which laws are</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> tested, interpreted and appl</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ied, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">gives contour and colour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> -</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> meaning - to the bare bones of the legislation introduced by Parliament.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The limits of the law are identified.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Inequalities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">addressed; injustices righted.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Public authorities </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who act unlawf</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ully</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ad</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">apt their policies accordingly.  I</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ndividuals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">know where they stand and how th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">e law will be applied to them</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, bringing certainty to the law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The provision of legal aid to allow cases to be brought, and case-law to develop, brings </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">considerable</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">enefit not only to the individual but to the public generally</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">he </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">proposals </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">contained in the ‘Transforming legal aid’ consultation </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">are particularly damaging to the rule of law.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  I will mention five of them.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">First, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">residence test</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">: those who have not la</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">wfully been in the country for 12 months or more will automatically be excluded from legal aid.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Although </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the proposal has been amended in relation to some of its worst aspects, there remains no legal aid for children above the age of 12 months, mentally disordered </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or other </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">disabled people </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">or those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">seek to bring proceedings challenging serious ill-treatmen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">t, such as the victim of sexual abuse at Yarl’s Wood IDC featured on the front cover of the Observer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> on 14 September 2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">No longer </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">can </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">we say, a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s Lord Scarman </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">did </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Khawaja</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in 1984, </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘Every person within the jurisdiction enjoys the equal protection of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">our laws.  There is no distinction between British nationals and others.  He who is subject to English law is entitled to its protection’.  </span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In my opinion this proposal is unlawful and discriminatory.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Second, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">exclusion of prisoners</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> from the availabil</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ity of legal aid.  As Sir Stephen Sedley points out in his foreword to the key </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">prison law </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">textbook</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">‘If the rule of law is to mean anything it has to mean that the prison system is no less answerable to the Courts than any other limb of the state’.  </span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Thi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s is an issue of principle, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and again I consider this proposal is unlawful and discriminatory.  B</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ut there is a practical issue as well.  In his post mortem report into the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Stangeways riot in 1990 Lord Woolf highlighted just how significant a contributor wa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s a burning sense of grievance on the part of prisoners that they were not being treated fairly.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">It can be no coincidence that since then, as case-law around the rights of prisoners ha</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> developed and lawyers have had the confidence to specialize in this a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rea, there have been no more serious riots.  With our prisons at capacity, it can only be a matter of time before unaddressed grievances will again lead to serious unrest.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Third, n</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">o </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">p</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ayment for judicial review cases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> before permission has been granted.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> proposal</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> is that, in those cases where a legal aid certificate is granted, lawyers acting for claimants will only be paid if permission is granted.  The idea is to reduce the number of ‘unmeritorious’ challenges.  In seeking to justify this</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> proposal </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the L</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ord Chancellor claimed </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on Radio 4 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">on 23 April 2013 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that of 11,359 judicial review claims</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in 2011-12</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, only 144 had succeeded at trial.  He did not mention that only 356 claims had, in fact, gone to trial - so the success rate for contested judicial reviews </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was over 40% - nor </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the fact </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">that of the other 11,000 claims, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">more than </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">half </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">were likely to have </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">settled </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in the claimant’s favour without the need for a trial.  Nor did he mention those </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">thousands of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">judicia</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">l review challenges that settle</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> in the individual’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> favour before the claim </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is even </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">issued.  With the original proposal, in none of these cases would the claimant’s lawyers be paid notwithstanding their ‘success’.  The Consultation paper suggests that claimant lawyers can recover their costs from the other</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> side, but this means that cases that have otherwise settled have to continue for the sole purpose of determining costs, running up </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">additional costs and taking up valuable Court time in the process.  Although the Government now suggests that in some of the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">se cases legal aid can be paid, this will only apply to cases that have been </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">issued.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In the case of challenges that have not been issued, to recover their costs from the other side claimant lawyers will have to issue the claim in order for a judge to make</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> a costs order in their favour</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> to recover anything at all</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">This will create further unnecessary costs and add to the burden on the Administrative Court.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the response of 145 </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Treasury Counsel </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">original </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Consultation this proposal was specifically op</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">posed on the basis it would make this area of law ‘unviable’ for practitioners.  We have already seen the closure of many firms, including </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">leading human rights barristers’ chambers, Tooks, caused by the squeeze on legal aid.  The implications for the d</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">evelopment of judicial review, and of the rule of law, are obvious.  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Fourth, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">removal of legal aid for borderline cases</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  At present, a case whose prospects cannot be put at higher than 50% can be funded if it is one raising substantial issues of wider</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> public importance</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> (SWPI)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  Many public law cases cannot be assessed as having prospects greater than 50% because the law is developing; this is particularly so in cases raising profound issues of human rights law.  For example, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I represented Debbie Purdy </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in her</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> 2009 challenge to the DPP’s prosecution policy on assisted suicide</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  We</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> lost at first instance and in the Court of Appeal, but succeeded in the House of Lords.  At any point before the House of Lords judgment it would not have been possible to asses</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">s the prospects at more than 50%.  I am</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> currently representing Paul Lamb and the family of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Tony Nicklinson </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">in their </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">challenge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">existing law criminalising e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">uthanasia and assisted suicide.  This </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">was only granted public funding on the basis it had borde</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">rline prospects but that it raised issues of SWPI.  Neither case would q</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ualify for legal aid if this proposal became law</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, nor would any case qualify for legal aid on an appeal where a first instance court or Court of Appeal has ruled against the individual</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.  It goes without saying that the Government is not precluded from appealing cases that are decided against it on this basis.</span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Fifth, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">the proposals are to be introduced by statutory instrument</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">, not by legislation, which is</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> itself is a matter of some considerable constitutional concern</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Parliament should scrutinise and debate proposals as controversial and potentially damaging as these.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">These changes go further than many of those introduced by the Legal Aid, Sentencing and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Punishment of Offenders Act 2012, which followed many hours of anguished debate and consideration in committee before it came into law.  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">A s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">tatutory </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">nstrument</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">is, to all intents and purposes, the creature of</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> the Minister who introduces it,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">explained b</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">y Lord Sumption in his speech in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Bank Mellat v HM Treasury </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">[2013] UKSC 38, para 43</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 19pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">“</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">... </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">a statutory instrument is the instrument of the minister ... who is empowered by the enabling Act to make it’.  </span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">Parliament’s powers to reject a SI are limited, depen</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ding upon whether the negative or affirmative procedure is adopted, and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">may </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">usually only reject it in its entirety rather than make amendments.  Parliamentary scrutiny is therefore substantially more limited.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 0pt 20pt; padding-left:1.25pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">For these reasons </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">I urge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">the Committee to rej</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">ect </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">these deeply flawed proposals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">24 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">From Barretry, Maintenance and Champerty</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> to Litigation Funding Harbour Litigation Funding First Annual Lecture Lord Neuberger, President of The Supreme Court Gray’s Inn, 9 May 2013</span></p><p style="margin:12pt 0pt 0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:'Times N